## ğŸ“Œ **1ï¸âƒ£ What does this command do?**

```bash
echo 'SUBSYSTEM=="usb", ATTR{idVendor}=="22d9", MODE="0666", GROUP="plugdev"' | sudo tee /etc/udev/rules.d/51-android-usb.rules
```

**Parts:**

* `echo '...'` â€” outputs the text:

  ```
  SUBSYSTEM=="usb", ATTR{idVendor}=="22d9", MODE="0666", GROUP="plugdev"
  ```
* `| sudo tee ...` â€” pipes (`|`) the output into `sudo tee ...`
  This writes the text **as root** to a new file:

  ```
  /etc/udev/rules.d/51-android-usb.rules
  ```

---

**Whatâ€™s inside the rule?**
This is a **udev rule** â€” udev is Linuxâ€™s device manager.

* `SUBSYSTEM=="usb"` â†’ Applies only to USB devices.
* `ATTR{idVendor}=="22d9"` â†’ Matches any USB device with **Vendor ID `22d9`** (for example, Infinix/Realme/Some brands).
* `MODE="0666"` â†’ Sets permissions: **read & write for everyone** (user/group/others).
* `GROUP="plugdev"` â†’ Makes the device belong to the `plugdev` group.

---

âœ… **Purpose:**
This makes the connected Android phoneâ€™s USB **accessible** to your user account without `sudo`.

If you **donâ€™t set this**, `adb` might say:

> `no permissions (user in plugdev group; are your udev rules wrong?)`

So this rule says:

> When I plug in my phone, give `plugdev` group full access.

**After this, `adb` can talk to your phone freely**.

---

## ğŸ“Œ **2ï¸âƒ£ How does React Native CLI connect to a phone over USB or Wi-Fi?**

**Basic flow:**

1. `adb` (`Android Debug Bridge`) talks to your phone.
2. `adb` needs USB access â†’ udev rule ensures you donâ€™t need `sudo`.
3. React Native CLI uses `adb` under the hood:

   * **Builds** your `.apk` using Gradle.
   * **Pushes** the `.apk` to your phone via `adb install`.
   * **Starts** the app on your phone.
   * Runs a **Metro Bundler** server on your dev machine (port 8081).

---

### âœ… **How does Wi-Fi debug work?**

* **First, you connect your phone by USB**, run:

  ```
  adb tcpip 5555
  ```

  This tells your phoneâ€™s `adb` daemon to listen over TCP port `5555`.

* Next, find your phoneâ€™s IP:

  ```
  adb shell ip route
  ```

  or check Wi-Fi settings.

* Connect over Wi-Fi:

  ```
  adb connect <PHONE_IP>:5555
  ```

Now your phone is accessible **wirelessly**, `adb` tunnels all commands over Wi-Fi.

The React Native CLI just uses this `adb` link:

* Build â†’ push â†’ run â†’ reload â†’ logcat

---

## âœ… **Why do we do this?**

* The udev rule makes `adb` talk to the phone **without sudo**.
* Wi-Fi mode is great when you want to debug **without a cable**.
* Same `adb` server â†’ same React Native Metro server â†’ same live reload and fast refresh.

---

## ğŸ“Œ **Key concept**

> **udev rule** â†’ gives your user permissions for USB `adb`
> **adb over TCP** â†’ enables wireless development
> **React Native CLI** â†’ uses `adb` + Metro to install, bundle, push updates

---

## ğŸ”‘ **Summary**

| Part                 | Role                                         |
